00:12:22.280 --> 00:12:26.160
A Story in Layers
the Artisan Hands

00:12:26.160 --> 00:12:29.380
that Make Japanese
Woodblock Prints.

00:12:30.820 --> 00:12:36.170
Making has become increasingly
invisible, take some examples

00:12:36.170 --> 00:12:40.100
of millennial making,
microchips, wear circuitry

00:12:40.100 --> 00:12:46.060
on their exterior, but their
machine built panels are

00:12:46.060 --> 00:12:49.700
so miniature they go
undetected by the naked eye.

00:12:49.700 --> 00:12:53.070
State-of-the-art kitchen
utensils we handle daily.

00:12:53.070 --> 00:12:57.350
such as cookware and knives
reflect aesthetic design.

00:12:57.350 --> 00:12:59.580
Yet how they are
made is imperceptible

00:12:59.580 --> 00:13:02.330
to the majority of users.

00:13:02.330 --> 00:13:05.970
Digital images on
our devices reformat

00:13:05.970 --> 00:13:09.070
into uniform pixels
the diverse mediums,

00:13:09.070 --> 00:13:12.240
for instance National
Gallery's favorite Renoirs,

00:13:12.240 --> 00:13:14.220
girl with the watering can,

00:13:14.220 --> 00:13:17.060
Mark Bradford's mixed-media
installation,

00:13:17.060 --> 00:13:19.490
which some of you may have
seen, Pickett's charge recently

00:13:19.490 --> 00:13:22.800
on display and at Hirshhorn,

00:13:22.800 --> 00:13:26.080
and here at the libraries we'll
see this afternoon afterwards

00:13:26.080 --> 00:13:31.220
Hokusai's iconic woodblock
print, great wave off Kanagawa

00:13:32.740 --> 00:13:34.270
which needs no introduction.

00:13:34.270 --> 00:13:39.730
The pixilation of which severs
viewers from engagement with all

00:13:39.730 --> 00:13:44.270
but the visual image often
fleeting or distorted at that.

00:13:44.270 --> 00:13:47.840
At least for now coding
sequences for images

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:50.460
that are foreign
languages for IT,

00:13:50.460 --> 00:13:54.910
safer IT specialists obscure
the size, depth, texture,

00:13:54.910 --> 00:13:57.820
color palette, individual
materials and even movement

00:13:57.820 --> 00:14:00.010
if you think of someone
like Calder.

00:14:00.010 --> 00:14:03.220
And the smell, I mean
prints have a good smell,

00:14:03.220 --> 00:14:06.010
they have smell of glue
and inks in the papers.

00:14:06.010 --> 00:14:09.640
Elements that reveal the
making behind an object

00:14:09.640 --> 00:14:14.110
and the hands invested
in its production.

00:14:14.110 --> 00:14:18.860
Reaction to this trend
is trendy and various.

00:14:18.860 --> 00:14:21.330
Richard Sennett's The Craftsman

00:14:21.330 --> 00:14:23.950
and Matthew Crawford's
Shop Class

00:14:23.950 --> 00:14:28.180
as Soulcraft have explored the
benefits of physical skills

00:14:28.180 --> 00:14:30.890
and apprenticeship
culture presaging

00:14:30.890 --> 00:14:35.070
or prompting a resurgence
in education about the value

00:14:35.070 --> 00:14:37.260
of specialized handwork.

00:14:37.260 --> 00:14:40.190
On the ground maker
spaces involve dimensions,

00:14:40.190 --> 00:14:44.420
outgrowths of the vibrant maker
movement satisfying an appetite

00:14:44.420 --> 00:14:47.110
for making from carpentry
to robots,

00:14:47.110 --> 00:14:50.890
organic materials
to recycled parts.

00:14:50.890 --> 00:14:52.810
More specific to the art world,

00:14:52.810 --> 00:14:56.420
in response to the restricted
experience of digitized works

00:14:56.420 --> 00:15:00.510
of art, research and development
of haptic technologies

00:15:00.510 --> 00:15:04.930
to enable experiencing the
tactile qualities of an object

00:15:04.930 --> 00:15:08.630
in digital form is
similarly vigorous.

00:15:08.630 --> 00:15:13.320
This expiration of making
points to intrinsic value

00:15:13.320 --> 00:15:17.790
in the handcrafted object itself
so ubiquitous today in Japan,

00:15:17.790 --> 00:15:21.640
especially as well as here
where glossy magazines

00:15:21.640 --> 00:15:25.850
and aesthetic books
fetishize the handmade.

00:15:25.850 --> 00:15:29.950
Known familiarly as ukiyo-e
traditional Japanese woodblock

00:15:29.950 --> 00:15:34.320
prints like Hokusai's wave
encompass visually complex

00:15:34.320 --> 00:15:39.230
and technically refined prints
roughly of the Edo period 1615

00:15:39.230 --> 00:15:42.610
to 1848 and then into the
modern period thereafter

00:15:42.610 --> 00:15:44.680
for 50 or so years.

00:15:44.680 --> 00:15:49.080
They fall into the broad
category of invisible making,

00:15:49.080 --> 00:15:53.050
that is to many viewers today
the mastery that ukiyo-e exhibit

00:15:53.050 --> 00:15:58.630
in combining materials and
techniques is both inscrutable

00:15:58.630 --> 00:16:02.990
and unimaginable not because
these images are mechanically

00:16:02.990 --> 00:16:07.080
reproduced, but because
they are wrought so finally

00:16:07.080 --> 00:16:11.670
by a multitude of hands skilled
in diverse tools, materials

00:16:11.670 --> 00:16:16.070
and methods that uninformed
viewers cannot apprehend

00:16:16.070 --> 00:16:17.580
their process.

00:16:17.580 --> 00:16:20.110
And so, traditional
woodblock print editions

00:16:20.110 --> 00:16:24.500
of ukiyo-e today can often
be mistaken as machine prints

00:16:24.500 --> 00:16:28.740
or even machine reproductions
of paintings.

00:16:28.740 --> 00:16:33.580
That is why master printer Keizo
Sato or excuse me Sato Keizo

00:16:33.580 --> 00:16:37.680
of Sato Woodblock Studio in
Kyoto insists that engagement

00:16:37.680 --> 00:16:41.510
with actual artworks ensures
the best form of study.

00:16:41.510 --> 00:16:43.990
That is also why
Sato reaches for one

00:16:43.990 --> 00:16:46.030
of his studio's favorite
printings

00:16:46.030 --> 00:16:50.820
of Hiroshige's landscape, a
view of Naruto at Awa province

00:16:50.820 --> 00:16:53.370
to demonstrate his point.

00:16:53.370 --> 00:16:58.080
Apart from its production notes,
commissioned in the early 1970's

00:16:58.080 --> 00:17:00.830
by a Tokyo publisher
for an initial order

00:17:00.830 --> 00:17:05.410
of 70 prints completed by
one carver and five printers

00:17:05.410 --> 00:17:08.850
and pulled 12 to 16
times from five blocks.

00:17:08.850 --> 00:17:12.170
It's prized for its Ichimon,
Bokashi, [inaudible],

00:17:12.170 --> 00:17:16.040
I've got several examples
here and the one highlighted

00:17:16.040 --> 00:17:20.320
in yellow is the one that
we can view in the print.

00:17:20.320 --> 00:17:25.980
So, this kind of straight
line color gradation

00:17:25.980 --> 00:17:31.580
across the top here you
can barely see it there,

00:17:31.580 --> 00:17:34.770
that challenging technique.

00:17:34.770 --> 00:17:38.740
The calibration of overall
color across the three sheets,

00:17:38.740 --> 00:17:43.450
so these each of these
is printed individually.

00:17:43.450 --> 00:17:46.490
But the color of the ocean
at the different points,

00:17:46.490 --> 00:17:51.090
the ocean line here this all
has to coordinate together.

00:17:51.090 --> 00:17:57.070
As well as the curved lines that
are meant to resemble flowers.

