to examine the multicolor image
on translucent natural paper

00:18:06.430 --> 00:18:10.100
and take in its unified
experience of the senses.

00:18:10.100 --> 00:18:13.480
Sato maintains we cannot
fully appreciate the work.

00:18:13.480 --> 00:18:17.390
From the artisan
standpoint, the materiality

00:18:17.390 --> 00:18:20.710
and techniques are not
surprisingly indivisible

00:18:20.710 --> 00:18:24.440
from the enjoyment of
the picture they support.

00:18:24.440 --> 00:18:27.460
I'd like to push Sato's
claim one step further to add

00:18:27.460 --> 00:18:31.190
that accessing the deep
knowledge of woodblock artisans

00:18:31.190 --> 00:18:34.290
or shokunin in the Japanese
expression themselves reveals

00:18:34.290 --> 00:18:37.290
meaning beyond both the distinct
visual appeal of ukiyo-e

00:18:37.290 --> 00:18:40.450
and the techniques
they preserve.

00:18:40.450 --> 00:18:43.800
And in a broader scheme I
want to consider a work of art

00:18:43.800 --> 00:18:47.330
that is also a sum of its
making is commanding relevance

00:18:47.330 --> 00:18:50.270
in an era where so much making
has gone beyond what we can

00:18:50.270 --> 00:18:53.160
picture or imagine.

00:18:53.160 --> 00:18:56.520
Let me begin by clarifying the
particular contemporary mode

00:18:56.520 --> 00:18:59.560
of ukiyo-e production
to which I refer today.

00:18:59.560 --> 00:19:02.810
What the Library of Congress
primarily has in its holdings,

00:19:02.810 --> 00:19:05.400
although Catherine also
pulled some of what we're --

00:19:05.400 --> 00:19:07.100
a similar mode that
we're going to look

00:19:07.100 --> 00:19:10.800
at today our ukiyo-e
contemporaneous with the air

00:19:10.800 --> 00:19:13.010
in which their designers
created images

00:19:13.010 --> 00:19:15.700
and artisans reproduce them.

00:19:15.700 --> 00:19:19.790
That is historic prints going
back as far as the Edo period.

00:19:19.790 --> 00:19:22.700
But what I focus on this
afternoon involves living

00:19:22.700 --> 00:19:27.550
artisans creating new
editions of these prints made

00:19:27.550 --> 00:19:31.530
from re-carved and reprinted
ukiyo-e known as fukkokuban.

00:19:31.530 --> 00:19:37.290
For the artisans who create
these prints translate a sheet

00:19:37.290 --> 00:19:42.070
as a reproduction or even
a facsimile is inaccurate

00:19:42.070 --> 00:19:45.730
because each is still
considered an original print in

00:19:45.730 --> 00:19:49.130
and of itself being faithful
to the ukiyo-e work by relying

00:19:49.130 --> 00:19:51.790
on the original design relying
on the original design go

00:19:51.790 --> 00:19:54.830
through various means of
transferring it to new blocks

00:19:54.830 --> 00:19:58.970
and yet being reinterpreted
by new sets of hands.

00:20:05.040 --> 00:20:06.360
Ukiyo-e fukkokuban produced

00:20:06.360 --> 00:20:08.460
at Sato's workshop
follow a similar,

00:20:08.460 --> 00:20:12.110
if impossibly exact
process of making

00:20:12.110 --> 00:20:13.750
that Edo Period artisans used

00:20:13.750 --> 00:20:17.210
to create water-based
multicolored woodblock prints

00:20:17.210 --> 00:20:19.190
like a view of Naruto.

00:20:19.190 --> 00:20:21.940
The process is commonly
explained in the context

00:20:21.940 --> 00:20:24.050
of a quartet of makers,
publisher,

00:20:24.050 --> 00:20:26.510
designer, carver and printer.

00:20:26.510 --> 00:20:29.230
Orchestrating the production
of an edition of prints,

00:20:29.230 --> 00:20:31.930
a publisher, the hanmoto
commissioned an image

00:20:31.930 --> 00:20:35.260
from a designer [inaudible] who
passed the draft of the image

00:20:35.260 --> 00:20:39.720
over to a single or a team
of specialized carvers

00:20:39.720 --> 00:20:43.410
who divide the design into
multiple blocks, sets of blocks

00:20:43.410 --> 00:20:46.150
that went to printers surishis

00:20:46.150 --> 00:20:49.310
who pulled carefully mixed
pigments 15 to 30 times

00:20:49.310 --> 00:20:53.140
for multiple blocks to the same
sheet to complete the process

00:20:53.140 --> 00:20:56.260
for an order into the
hundreds of sheets.

00:20:56.260 --> 00:21:01.250
And Catherine has very happily

00:21:01.250 --> 00:21:04.160
on my part pulled an
Acornian [phonetic] piece

00:21:04.160 --> 00:21:07.440
that I think she's going
to put out later and some

00:21:07.440 --> 00:21:08.800
of you may well have
seen these before

00:21:08.800 --> 00:21:12.020
where it traces the buildup of
blocks from the light colors

00:21:12.020 --> 00:21:13.800
until you get these
very brilliant colors,

00:21:13.800 --> 00:21:18.090
the very delicate process
of taking that same sheet

00:21:18.090 --> 00:21:20.570
and adding an additional
impression to it.

00:21:20.570 --> 00:21:23.240
This I thought was another
way of looking at it

00:21:23.240 --> 00:21:25.980
where you're looking at the
carver's blocks and the colors.

00:21:25.980 --> 00:21:30.290
Each block that sometimes
impressions are taken

00:21:30.290 --> 00:21:32.030
of you know can be two, three,

00:21:32.030 --> 00:21:37.010
four times for more complex
works in the same field

00:21:37.010 --> 00:21:38.940
and then the colors
gradually built up.

00:21:38.940 --> 00:21:41.800
For those of you who are
familiar with these blocks,

00:21:41.800 --> 00:21:43.100
you've seen them, you work

00:21:43.100 --> 00:21:46.810
with them you will also you
know there's detail and story

00:21:46.810 --> 00:21:49.870
within the blocks
themselves, so it's also nice

00:21:49.870 --> 00:21:51.170
to be able to look at those.

00:21:51.170 --> 00:21:53.730
For those of you who you
know may look at these blocks

00:21:53.730 --> 00:21:56.330
and not read the clues on
them, but you're curious

00:21:56.330 --> 00:21:58.050
and you have questions,
I'd be happy to go look

00:21:58.050 --> 00:22:00.640
at them with you afterwards.

00:22:00.640 --> 00:22:06.710
That gives you a picture
of the story of making

00:22:06.710 --> 00:22:08.160
and then we get to
the final print.

00:22:08.160 --> 00:22:10.770
So, this particular story,
this simplified story is

00:22:10.770 --> 00:22:14.910
so oft repeated that I wanted
to update it and expand it based

00:22:14.910 --> 00:22:21.140
on ukiyo-e production as it has
been transmitted to us today.

00:22:21.140 --> 00:22:25.840
But first, glimpses from Edo's
past establishing standards

00:22:25.840 --> 00:22:29.510
as designers such as Kitagawa
Utamaro Utagawa Kunisada took it

00:22:29.510 --> 00:22:34.550
upon themselves to depict
their flourishing industry.

00:22:34.550 --> 00:22:36.840
And some of these
again if you're working

00:22:36.840 --> 00:22:39.390
in this field you may well have
seen these, I'm going to look

00:22:39.390 --> 00:22:41.680
at these in a very
rapid way today,

00:22:41.680 --> 00:22:47.100
but there's extraordinary detail
that tells so many aspects

00:22:47.100 --> 00:22:49.350
of what they saw
themselves doing.

00:22:49.350 --> 00:22:54.310
So, Utamaro's pair of triptychs
from the series the cultivation

00:22:54.310 --> 00:22:56.610
of brocade prints and I've
got these broken up here just

00:22:56.610 --> 00:22:59.210
because it's detailed,
so here are the first two

00:22:59.210 --> 00:23:04.270
and then the second or
the third sheet of these.

00:23:04.270 --> 00:23:08.210
Utamaro characterizes the
production of nishiki-e

00:23:08.210 --> 00:23:11.540
or brocade pictures,
brocade meaning multicolor

00:23:11.540 --> 00:23:14.480
like the woven brocade
of a kimono obi.

00:23:14.480 --> 00:23:19.550
Through the particular work
of the designer, the carver

00:23:19.550 --> 00:23:24.770
and then here you have the paper
sizer to the commercial side,

00:23:24.770 --> 00:23:29.080
well you have the printing
here and then the novelty shops

00:23:29.080 --> 00:23:33.140
that sold these popular
prints and the customers.

00:23:33.140 --> 00:23:37.400
The most conspicuous
aspect is Utamaro's pairing,

00:23:37.400 --> 00:23:40.680
the woodblock shokunin
by casting them

00:23:40.680 --> 00:23:42.600
as delicately wrought
[inaudible],

00:23:42.600 --> 00:23:44.710
beauties are courtesans

00:23:44.710 --> 00:23:48.620
who of course were a very
popular genre in ukiyo-e.

00:23:48.620 --> 00:23:51.230
In a similar tongue-in-cheek
arrangement

00:23:51.230 --> 00:23:54.110
of [inaudible] Kunisada
creates this tryptic

00:23:54.110 --> 00:23:57.040
and up-to-date parody
of the four classes

00:23:57.040 --> 00:24:00.980
where the artisan class
appears as ukiyo-e artisans

00:24:00.980 --> 00:24:04.570
who are almost secondary to
the wealth and variety of tools

00:24:04.570 --> 00:24:07.640
and materials show that
support their craft.

00:24:07.640 --> 00:24:12.110
A variety of brushes, sizing,
paper, wood blocks, mallets,

00:24:12.110 --> 00:24:18.460
knives, gouges, chisels,
mallets, Sumi color pigments,

00:24:18.460 --> 00:24:21.800
[inaudible] wet stone,
animal glue known as nikawa

00:24:21.800 --> 00:24:24.570
and printing and
carving tables designed

00:24:24.570 --> 00:24:28.560
to aid physical labor
of each specialty.

00:24:28.560 --> 00:24:30.140
Beyond every one of those tools

00:24:30.140 --> 00:24:32.430
or materials were
individual artisans trained

00:24:32.430 --> 00:24:35.350
in their own particular
specialty

00:24:35.350 --> 00:24:38.450
that go beyond this notion
of the quartet, which I just

00:24:38.450 --> 00:24:40.690
because I haven't because I
think it's a beautiful book I

00:24:40.690 --> 00:24:41.990
wanted to just point this out.

00:24:41.990 --> 00:24:45.510
This is a fairly new book
by Julie Davis who's at Penn

00:24:45.510 --> 00:24:51.890
and works very deeply in the
art historical stories of prints

00:24:51.890 --> 00:24:57.130
and she's also pushing
this notion of this idea

00:24:57.130 --> 00:25:00.190
of the quartet that
has defined printmaking

00:25:00.190 --> 00:25:04.090
or ukiyo-e making
for a long time.

00:25:04.090 --> 00:25:09.160
We have later versions, I've
got my buttons mixed up here,

00:25:09.160 --> 00:25:12.470
to become a little
bit more naturalistic

00:25:12.470 --> 00:25:14.890
and this I think sort of
animates the physical labor

00:25:14.890 --> 00:25:17.400
of the work, it can be
very labor-intensive.

00:25:17.400 --> 00:25:19.680
They also include
additional artifacts,

00:25:19.680 --> 00:25:23.610
such as the handwoven
encasements of paper over here

00:25:23.610 --> 00:25:28.890
and then you have this man with
the cleaver clipping the edges

00:25:28.890 --> 00:25:31.180
that was important to
these very clean edges then

00:25:31.180 --> 00:25:33.330
when they went off for sales.

00:25:33.330 --> 00:25:40.040
The hibachis here that served
both to keep the artisans warm

00:25:40.040 --> 00:25:43.250
and to melt down, keep their
nikawa, their glue melted.

00:25:43.250 --> 00:25:46.300
And then the functional
accessory of piece is

00:25:46.300 --> 00:25:48.670
to the printing table, so this
is something a little more

00:25:48.670 --> 00:25:51.920
modest, something that you
would see more probably

00:25:51.920 --> 00:25:55.260
in the 10's, 20's, 30's.

00:25:55.260 --> 00:26:02.140
And this kind of -- in this
previous example here you can

00:26:02.140 --> 00:26:06.360
see the documentation of those
kinds of aspects of the printer

00:26:06.360 --> 00:26:10.370
that became very codified
and diagramed later.

00:26:10.370 --> 00:26:13.820
Apart from a few illusions
and updates these items

00:26:13.820 --> 00:26:16.780
and processes are
still in use today.

00:26:16.780 --> 00:26:19.980
What understanding of ukiyo-e
then do woodblock artisans

00:26:19.980 --> 00:26:24.170
practicing today impart and how
does their intimate view ascribe

00:26:24.170 --> 00:26:26.150
value to what they
produce in this era?

00:26:26.150 --> 00:26:30.780
Our first stop for the living
artisan's perspective is Sato

00:26:30.780 --> 00:26:35.790
Keizo's shop just behind Kyoto's
old geisha quarters of Gion.

00:26:35.790 --> 00:26:40.230
Sixty years ago, Sato's
father Tiazo moved his family

00:26:40.230 --> 00:26:41.590
and print studio together

00:26:41.590 --> 00:26:45.010
into a typical post-World War
II house constructed of wood

00:26:45.010 --> 00:26:46.920
and corrugated aluminum.

00:26:46.920 --> 00:26:49.790
A modest signboard above the
door still identifies the

00:26:49.790 --> 00:26:53.080
structure as Sato
Woodblock Studio.

00:26:53.080 --> 00:26:57.520
Sato himself can only claim to
be a second-generation shokunin

00:26:57.520 --> 00:27:00.930
or artisan, a lineage
that is unimpressive

00:27:00.930 --> 00:27:03.610
up against the dynastic
handicraft families

00:27:03.610 --> 00:27:05.690
that characterize Kyoto.

00:27:05.690 --> 00:27:08.920
Technically, however,
Sato descended

00:27:08.920 --> 00:27:12.010
from a Tokyo area shokunin
that can be traced back

00:27:12.010 --> 00:27:13.620
at least five generations.

00:27:13.620 --> 00:27:17.070
And what I have pictured here,
I don't know if the yellow,

00:27:17.070 --> 00:27:18.930
the highlight is
coming through here,

00:27:18.930 --> 00:27:21.230
but you have his lineage traced.

00:27:21.230 --> 00:27:23.260
This was actually
machine printed,

00:27:23.260 --> 00:27:25.980
but as you can tell it was
a handwritten genealogy

00:27:25.980 --> 00:27:32.690
from the early 1980's when a lot
of the shokunin were dying out

00:27:32.690 --> 00:27:36.780
and realized they wanted
to capture these histories.

00:27:36.780 --> 00:27:40.370
Of the 70 odd woodblock artisans
who still practice the art

00:27:40.370 --> 00:27:41.780
and craft between Tokyo

00:27:41.780 --> 00:27:47.750
and Kyoto today three printers
have apprenticed under Sato.

00:27:47.750 --> 00:27:54.970
And at this time, he --
excuse me, there we go.

00:28:06.060 --> 00:28:11.950
He has four printers, two
male and two females ranging

00:28:11.950 --> 00:28:15.710
from their 20's to 50's, three
of whom graduated university

00:28:15.710 --> 00:28:20.380
as artists and opted to embark
on apprenticeships instead

00:28:20.380 --> 00:28:23.170
and all of whom must
go through the rigor

00:28:23.170 --> 00:28:27.360
of learning the refined
skills of printing ukiyo-e.

00:28:27.360 --> 00:28:29.170
While the market
for new printings

00:28:29.170 --> 00:28:32.720
of ukiyo-e continues downsize
the more famous series

00:28:32.720 --> 00:28:37.540
of Hokusai Katshushika, such
as Mr. Nakayama's printing here

00:28:37.540 --> 00:28:42.510
and then you can see the very
familiar finished piece here.

00:28:42.510 --> 00:28:47.880
One of his fellow
printers Hirai opened with.

00:28:47.880 --> 00:28:57.580
They are still required
to study these prints.

00:28:57.580 --> 00:29:01.750
And they're commissioned
exercises to continue

00:29:01.750 --> 00:29:04.650
to hone the refined skills
of this cultural heritage.

00:29:04.650 --> 00:29:07.120
And I just wanted to
share this piece with you

00:29:07.120 --> 00:29:09.900
by a Finnish contemporary
artist,

00:29:09.900 --> 00:29:13.080
more of a graphic design artist
who has trained extensively

00:29:13.080 --> 00:29:14.490
in traditional techniques.

00:29:14.490 --> 00:29:18.140
And part of her cache of
teaching tools is these cards

00:29:18.140 --> 00:29:21.290
that she's made to represent.

00:29:21.290 --> 00:29:25.210
This is only one portion
of the 50 odd techniques

00:29:25.210 --> 00:29:27.740
that she herself has
documented and there are those

00:29:27.740 --> 00:29:29.170
that extend beyond that.

00:29:29.170 --> 00:29:32.320
So, this is the reason so
much of this commissioning

00:29:32.320 --> 00:29:36.150
of these old ukiyo-e
are being done today.

00:29:36.150 --> 00:29:40.190
Contemporary printers today
approach orders for ukiyo-e

00:29:40.190 --> 00:29:43.470
with a consultation
pooling their knowledge

00:29:43.470 --> 00:29:46.330
to discern what combination
of techniques is most likely

00:29:46.330 --> 00:29:48.400
to achieve the effects
of the original.

00:29:48.400 --> 00:29:51.850
And here's one working
in process here

00:29:51.850 --> 00:29:56.550
where you have the sample,
this one of the originals

00:29:56.550 --> 00:29:58.490
that came probably
from the publisher

00:29:58.490 --> 00:30:02.040
who made the request most likely
out of Tokyo or Kyoto today.

00:30:02.040 --> 00:30:03.950
And then you have
the prints coming off

00:30:03.950 --> 00:30:07.280
where the printer is
checking the color and sort

00:30:07.280 --> 00:30:09.960
of the overall flavor of
the print against the one

00:30:09.960 --> 00:30:14.010
that they're aiming to recreate.

00:30:14.010 --> 00:30:17.630
They examine the
original paper I order

00:30:17.630 --> 00:30:20.470
to assess how they should match
it by color, weight and texture

00:30:20.470 --> 00:30:22.530
and sometimes they don't
want to match it at all

00:30:22.530 --> 00:30:24.490
because in different eras
there were different qualities

00:30:24.490 --> 00:30:28.500
of paper and that paper
is one area for example

00:30:28.500 --> 00:30:30.080
that has become much
more standardized

00:30:30.080 --> 00:30:34.620
because over the years they've
learned what works, what sells,

00:30:34.620 --> 00:30:36.380
and above all in this case

00:30:36.380 --> 00:30:40.100
for preserving what
is going to last.

00:30:40.100 --> 00:30:42.030
They analyze the
color palette based

00:30:42.030 --> 00:30:44.960
on an original sample
though do not aim

00:30:44.960 --> 00:30:47.930
to reproduce the
exact colors visible,

00:30:47.930 --> 00:30:50.580
rather they mix colors they
determine are authentic

00:30:50.580 --> 00:30:55.380
to print before fading, as well
as to adapt to current tastes.

00:30:55.380 --> 00:31:00.010
They aim for consistency of
each color across an average run

00:31:00.010 --> 00:31:05.760
of 70 to 100 prints at a time,
as well as across the entirety

00:31:05.760 --> 00:31:10.210
of prints that compose
a particular series.

00:31:10.210 --> 00:31:13.020
Above all, is the
collective work

00:31:13.020 --> 00:31:15.970
that cannot adhere
solely to a single vision.

00:31:15.970 --> 00:31:18.000
The style unique to each artisan

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:22.060
or their [inaudible] infuses
new paintings or new printings

00:31:22.060 --> 00:31:23.980
with fresh originality.

00:31:23.980 --> 00:31:27.520
A hokusai or [inaudible] to
be sure differs from artisan

00:31:27.520 --> 00:31:32.810
to artisan or network of
artisans to network of artisans.

00:31:32.810 --> 00:31:36.150
To be able to produce these
prints Sato Studio operates

00:31:36.150 --> 00:31:39.400
within a traditional network
of mostly local shokunin

00:31:39.400 --> 00:31:42.070
who [inaudible] relies on
additionally for his paper,

00:31:42.070 --> 00:31:45.170
brushes, glue, Sumi
and color pigments.

00:31:45.170 --> 00:31:49.640
For paper he has a standing
order for a particular variety

00:31:49.640 --> 00:31:53.330
of washi known hosho
made of mulberry fiber.

00:31:53.330 --> 00:31:57.290
It is handmade by
papermaker Iwano Ichibei

00:31:57.290 --> 00:32:02.620
in the neighboring region of
[inaudible] and he's also a part

00:32:02.620 --> 00:32:08.350
of the living national treasure,
echelon of shokunin Japanese

00:32:08.350 --> 00:32:13.520
so he has a story
behind him as well.

00:32:13.520 --> 00:32:16.220
And the papermaking of
this particular village,

00:32:16.220 --> 00:32:19.240
particularly this hosho
variety that is so prized

00:32:19.240 --> 00:32:23.830
for woodblock printmaking is
of a cultural and a local level

00:32:23.830 --> 00:32:31.270
that there's a shrine that is
devoted to celebration of it

00:32:31.270 --> 00:32:33.270
with annual festivals
where the fresh sheets

00:32:33.270 --> 00:32:37.490
of paper are brought up
to the shrine as a means

00:32:37.490 --> 00:32:42.010
of Thanksgiving, so this
is serious business.

00:32:42.010 --> 00:32:44.180
Sato is clear about
his preference

00:32:44.180 --> 00:32:48.460
for Ichibei's costly paper
over more economical options.

00:32:48.460 --> 00:32:51.760
Its consistency of color which
you can see it's difficult here,

00:32:51.760 --> 00:32:53.630
but there's a real if you
were to look at this pail

00:32:53.630 --> 00:32:57.910
versus someone else's pail
the quality, the color,

00:32:57.910 --> 00:33:01.160
the very softness, the
consistency of texture.

00:33:01.160 --> 00:33:03.270
Also, the fiber length
and the linkage

00:33:03.270 --> 00:33:04.940
of those fibers are critical

00:33:04.940 --> 00:33:08.260
to pulling a perfect
impression sheet after sheet.

00:33:08.260 --> 00:33:09.800
And you know unlike an artist

00:33:09.800 --> 00:33:12.730
who may be seeking something
different, something surprising

00:33:12.730 --> 00:33:19.030
or something not precise
across several sheets they want

00:33:19.030 --> 00:33:22.320
that perfect turnout, so that
consistent quality is crucial.

00:33:22.320 --> 00:33:27.230
For pigments, Sato strolls 300
meters up the main intersection

00:33:27.230 --> 00:33:29.940
to Adachi Pigment Shop.

00:33:29.940 --> 00:33:34.800
Okay, so we've got Iwano here
with his wife pulling the paper

00:33:34.800 --> 00:33:36.850
and you can see the
stacks here and how smooth,

00:33:36.850 --> 00:33:38.230
it's difficult again
in this light,

00:33:38.230 --> 00:33:40.780
but how smooth that quality is.

00:33:40.780 --> 00:33:42.260
And then up the street

00:33:42.260 --> 00:33:45.220
from Sato's workshop
you have a pigment shop

00:33:45.220 --> 00:33:49.200
and although Adachi here has a
pamphlet exhibiting nearly 50

00:33:49.200 --> 00:33:53.470
exquisite color samples true
to the color wheel's claim

00:33:53.470 --> 00:33:56.720
or largely true,
it only takes five

00:33:56.720 --> 00:33:59.500
to generate the spectrum
of colors in ukiyo-e.

00:33:59.500 --> 00:34:04.040
Prussian blue, ocher, carmine
red, a resin like yellow

00:34:04.040 --> 00:34:06.880
and iron oxide burnt umber.

00:34:06.880 --> 00:34:13.500
Mixing the pigments with nikawa,
here are the commercial versions

00:34:13.500 --> 00:34:19.030
of the nikawa, the animal glue,
are also supplied by Adachi

00:34:19.030 --> 00:34:22.990
and he supplies it from another
shokunin craft now gone more

00:34:22.990 --> 00:34:25.640
industrial in Hyogo Prefecture

00:34:25.640 --> 00:34:30.710
where the malodorous substance
was once made from horse bone

00:34:30.710 --> 00:34:35.020
by Japanese, Japan's
Burakumin underclass.

00:34:35.020 --> 00:34:37.710
Sumi -- here's some
more examples

00:34:37.710 --> 00:34:43.580
of the nikawa in
its various forms.

00:34:43.580 --> 00:34:47.740
Sumi is another carefully
tended ingredient right

00:34:47.740 --> 00:34:49.450
and can be difficult
to deal with.

00:34:49.450 --> 00:34:52.540
If the grains are too coarse
Sato explains they do not

00:34:52.540 --> 00:34:54.390
generate the fine
[inaudible] necessary

00:34:54.390 --> 00:34:59.180
to capture ukiyo-e's bold black
outlines nor evenness of mixture

00:34:59.180 --> 00:35:03.250
in order to produce the same
result again, sheet after sheet.

00:35:03.250 --> 00:35:07.280
Three decades ago,
Sato met a Mr. Matsui

00:35:07.280 --> 00:35:12.030
from the sumi maker Boku-undo
located in nearby Nara.

00:35:12.030 --> 00:35:15.530
Sato was determined to calibrate
the portion of [inaudible] black

00:35:15.530 --> 00:35:20.020
or soot, the base of
sumi, nikawa and water

00:35:20.020 --> 00:35:21.950
to best suit his printing

00:35:21.950 --> 00:35:24.990
where today more standard
versions are premixed

00:35:24.990 --> 00:35:28.520
to favor the expressive effects
in calligraphy and ink painting,

00:35:28.520 --> 00:35:30.890
which there are just so
many more practitioners

00:35:30.890 --> 00:35:33.410
so it's being driven by
the market of course.

00:35:33.410 --> 00:35:36.880
Matsui mixed up a custom recipe
for Sato that he has used ever

00:35:36.880 --> 00:35:39.520
since and you can see
the various mixes here

00:35:39.520 --> 00:35:42.780
and then he's got his
bottle of Matsui special mix

00:35:42.780 --> 00:35:45.060
that he's pouring from.

00:35:45.060 --> 00:35:48.910
In the printer's world
beyond the various brushes,

00:35:48.910 --> 00:35:51.480
each with their own purpose
and histories of making

00:35:51.480 --> 00:35:52.780
that I'm going to leave

00:35:52.780 --> 00:35:58.400
for another time is the
burnishing pad, the baren.

00:35:58.400 --> 00:36:00.790
And unlike some of the
other printing tools

00:36:00.790 --> 00:36:04.260
that may be considered more
fungible the baren is unique

00:36:04.260 --> 00:36:06.980
to Japanese woodblock
printmaking and essential

00:36:06.980 --> 00:36:10.480
to executing ukiyo-e's
cache of techniques.

00:36:10.480 --> 00:36:13.570
Its curious construction
incorporates two varieties

00:36:13.570 --> 00:36:19.510
of bamboo fiber that are rare
today, [inaudible], washi,

00:36:19.510 --> 00:36:24.820
bracken root, starch
powder, fermented persimmon,

00:36:24.820 --> 00:36:28.000
black lacquer and camellia oil.

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:30.650
The materials are
worked into improbable

00:36:30.650 --> 00:36:33.760
and laborious combination
of parts snugly fit together

00:36:33.760 --> 00:36:37.910
in a durable disk that
can withstand the pressure

00:36:37.910 --> 00:36:40.960
of a printer's hand for decades.

00:36:40.960 --> 00:36:42.940
The finished baren is
yet unrevealing though

00:36:42.940 --> 00:36:46.590
because its innards
pictured here that's

00:36:46.590 --> 00:36:50.000
where the efficacy lies.

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:54.680
The crucial rationale behind
the baren being these nubbins

00:36:54.680 --> 00:36:59.280
of this woven bamboo, this
braided bamboo, the [inaudible],

00:36:59.280 --> 00:37:03.020
the part that sticks out that
emerged when different braids

00:37:03.020 --> 00:37:06.020
of bamboo are coiled
into its tight disk.

00:37:06.020 --> 00:37:09.570
These nubbins create multiple
pressure points that pulse

00:37:09.570 --> 00:37:12.670
over the woodblock surface
forcing the colorant

00:37:12.670 --> 00:37:14.640
into the paper fibers.

00:37:14.640 --> 00:37:18.120
Equally critical are
the minute hollow spaces

00:37:18.120 --> 00:37:21.280
around the nubbin
simultaneously working to allow

00:37:21.280 --> 00:37:24.480
for enough release of pressure
in order to prevent the paper

00:37:24.480 --> 00:37:26.740
from sticking to a dampen block.

00:37:26.740 --> 00:37:29.990
So, it's a pretty sophisticated
mechanism accomplishing many

00:37:29.990 --> 00:37:32.950
things all at once.

00:37:32.950 --> 00:37:36.350
Goto Hidehiko, Japan's
only artisan devoted solely

00:37:36.350 --> 00:37:40.220
to baren making and he
has a book on the subject,

00:37:40.220 --> 00:37:43.190
characterizes the baren as
a tool that doesn't stand

00:37:43.190 --> 00:37:47.390
out for its consequentiality,
but in actuality is a tool

00:37:47.390 --> 00:37:50.450
that has continued in
use since the Edo Period.

00:37:50.450 --> 00:37:52.820
That is to say and this
is how he describes it,

00:37:52.820 --> 00:37:56.300
one with a depth that
is packed with wisdom.

00:37:56.300 --> 00:38:00.460
Like paper he explains the baren
occupies a hollowed position

00:38:00.460 --> 00:38:02.660
in the woodblock
printer's craft.

00:38:02.660 --> 00:38:06.040
Where washi is the
ultimate long life medium

00:38:06.040 --> 00:38:09.900
to convey the artist's
vision the baren is cast

00:38:09.900 --> 00:38:13.140
and as the alter-ego
of the printer,

00:38:13.140 --> 00:38:16.000
the trace of the
printer's hand testimony

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:20.480
to the printer's labor,
mark of the [audio breaks].

00:38:20.480 --> 00:38:24.660
Goto adds that a good baren
finesses the work of the carver

00:38:24.660 --> 00:38:29.090
and I like that it's not all
about the printer it goes back

00:38:29.090 --> 00:38:31.010
to the carver by
expressing the hand,

00:38:31.010 --> 00:38:33.110
the lines cut by the carver.

00:38:33.110 --> 00:38:37.940
Because printers finish an image
by pulling it in brilliant color

00:38:37.940 --> 00:38:42.290
to paper with a symbolic
baren their image has come

00:38:42.290 --> 00:38:45.410
to represent the
essence of the craft.

00:38:45.410 --> 00:38:48.760
But backing up to consider
the block before the print.

00:38:48.760 --> 00:38:51.670
Carver Fujisawa Hiroshi
who collaborates

00:38:51.670 --> 00:38:55.450
with the Sato Studio on print
commissions has his own take

00:38:55.450 --> 00:38:58.010
on woodblock in ukiyo-e.

00:38:58.010 --> 00:39:01.010
Fujisawa is considered
number one in Japan,

00:39:01.010 --> 00:39:04.310
[inaudible] dai-ichi among
traditional woodblock carvers,

00:39:04.310 --> 00:39:06.410
though his beginnings
were modest.

00:39:06.410 --> 00:39:09.920
He came to his craft as
one of the last generation

00:39:09.920 --> 00:39:14.360
of postwar shokunin
in the mid-1960's

00:39:14.360 --> 00:39:18.360
who selected a vocational
path after middle school.

00:39:18.360 --> 00:39:21.340
Even though he enjoys reading
art books today he describes

00:39:21.340 --> 00:39:25.490
himself as an old-fashioned
type without any education.

00:39:25.490 --> 00:39:26.990
When he came of age

00:39:26.990 --> 00:39:29.300
as an artisan it would
have been unimaginable

00:39:29.300 --> 00:39:32.410
that a shokunin could be
a university graduate.

00:39:32.410 --> 00:39:36.090
Fujisawa sees his spiritual
dimension to his craft

00:39:36.090 --> 00:39:38.510
through the Japanese
concept of kokoro

00:39:38.510 --> 00:39:40.930
or heart mind or mindfulness.

00:39:40.930 --> 00:39:44.780
He expresses his kokoro
through transmission

00:39:44.780 --> 00:39:47.280
from his dedicated work
of the hand facilitated

00:39:47.280 --> 00:39:51.740
by his prize tools, each
with their own handmade story

00:39:51.740 --> 00:39:54.110
of course, to the
natural materials

00:39:54.110 --> 00:39:56.070
that he handles with them.

00:39:56.070 --> 00:39:59.640
As the carver he
approaches his work

00:39:59.640 --> 00:40:02.040
to ease the way for the printer.

00:40:02.040 --> 00:40:03.650
So, there's this this thinking

00:40:03.650 --> 00:40:08.730
of this team along the way
helping each other out,

00:40:08.730 --> 00:40:10.570
anticipating areas of the block

00:40:10.570 --> 00:40:12.880
where the printer may
encounter difficulties

00:40:12.880 --> 00:40:15.240
in effecting particular
techniques

00:40:15.240 --> 00:40:18.160
and even manipulating
carved portion

00:40:18.160 --> 00:40:21.450
to serve the carver's own
interpretation of the image.

00:40:21.450 --> 00:40:26.310
He has that artists in the past
praised carvers and printers

00:40:26.310 --> 00:40:29.900
because they had the capacity
to correct the artist's work,

00:40:29.900 --> 00:40:33.190
just as a translator has
the possibility of improving

00:40:33.190 --> 00:40:35.920
on the original of
the author's text.

00:40:35.920 --> 00:40:39.050
But Fujisawa concedes he
would never tell the artist

00:40:39.050 --> 00:40:41.560
because the aim was
to please him or her.

00:40:41.560 --> 00:40:46.450
In the traditional woodblock
process before the carver was

00:40:46.450 --> 00:40:50.020
the planer this shokunin
was essentially a carpenter

00:40:50.020 --> 00:40:51.910
who possessed the
specialized skill

00:40:51.910 --> 00:40:56.190
to prepare wood especially
for woodblocks.

00:40:56.190 --> 00:41:00.920
According to the 1929 handbook
Nishiki-e Carving and Printing

00:41:00.920 --> 00:41:04.820
in the Edo Period these
[inaudible] or plank men apart

00:41:04.820 --> 00:41:07.030
from harvesting and
aging the wood

00:41:07.030 --> 00:41:12.240
to minimize warping produced
blocks in the appropriate size

00:41:12.240 --> 00:41:14.240
and thickness specifically

00:41:14.240 --> 00:41:17.180
for this industry of
multicolor prints.

00:41:17.180 --> 00:41:19.330
But the real expertise came

00:41:19.330 --> 00:41:21.680
in the way they applied
different planes,

00:41:21.680 --> 00:41:24.880
the planing process to
prepare the woodblock.

00:41:24.880 --> 00:41:29.330
Above all, the woodblock had to
be absolutely smooth and even

00:41:29.330 --> 00:41:32.110
to avoid any pooling
on its surface,

00:41:32.110 --> 00:41:35.900
a condition that neither machine
planing is quite fine enough

00:41:35.900 --> 00:41:38.270
to render today nor
can be matched

00:41:38.270 --> 00:41:40.250
by substituting present-day
timbers

00:41:40.250 --> 00:41:43.090
for building construction.

00:41:43.090 --> 00:41:46.110
Like the Chinese gold
standard of pear wood

00:41:46.110 --> 00:41:49.130
or [inaudible] the Japanese
preference for [inaudible],

00:41:49.130 --> 00:41:53.720
the mountain cherry type
of timber was practical.

00:41:53.720 --> 00:41:56.810
It was a plentiful
indigenous timber harvested

00:41:56.810 --> 00:42:00.090
from nearby mountains that
offered a suitable hardness

00:42:00.090 --> 00:42:03.590
to facilitate carving while
still supporting the hairpin

00:42:03.590 --> 00:42:06.520
relief in ukiyo-e in
sustaining the wear

00:42:06.520 --> 00:42:08.250
and tear of large print runs.

00:42:08.250 --> 00:42:11.240
And I noticed some of the prints
that Catherine pulled today,

00:42:11.240 --> 00:42:13.750
these hairpin lines,
I mean there were some

00:42:13.750 --> 00:42:16.390
that were even thinner than
a hairpin I think in some

00:42:16.390 --> 00:42:19.750
of the patterns on
the textile designs.

00:42:19.750 --> 00:42:23.180
So, when you go out just zero in
on the fineness of those lines

00:42:23.180 --> 00:42:26.700
and that the cherry
wood can withstand

00:42:26.700 --> 00:42:29.970
that so those little
pieces don't pop off.

00:42:29.970 --> 00:42:33.310
Fujisawa considers
[inaudible] Japanese magnolia,

00:42:33.310 --> 00:42:34.730
another desirable hardwood,

00:42:34.730 --> 00:42:37.710
although he declares
it's no good for Utamaro.

00:42:37.710 --> 00:42:40.660
[Inaudible] further he
suggests another variety,

00:42:40.660 --> 00:42:44.580
a type of boxwood known as
tsuge also pleasantly hard,

00:42:44.580 --> 00:42:47.030
but the trouble with [inaudible]
lies in the trunk diameter

00:42:47.030 --> 00:42:50.930
that only matures about
15 to 20 centimeters.

00:42:50.930 --> 00:42:53.980
So, you know, if you're doing
small prints that works,

00:42:53.980 --> 00:42:56.520
but in the standard
of this oban size,

00:42:56.520 --> 00:43:00.010
the standard ukiyo-e size
it's simply too small.

00:43:00.010 --> 00:43:03.990
So, you can see how all of these
things come down to us today.

00:43:03.990 --> 00:43:09.540
Unlike Western-style engraving
that uses that horizontal cut

00:43:09.540 --> 00:43:13.410
on the top the custom of
ukiyo-e is a vertical cut,

00:43:13.410 --> 00:43:17.880
and specifically an outside,
the outer side of a tree trunk.

00:43:17.880 --> 00:43:19.870
There are more practical
reasons for this,

00:43:19.870 --> 00:43:22.300
among them being the vertical
cut with its alignment

00:43:22.300 --> 00:43:26.500
of green made a block softer
and easier to carve enabling

00:43:26.500 --> 00:43:29.370
for speed and quick turnover,
which is less an issue today

00:43:29.370 --> 00:43:31.100
but it was an issue
when this was a vibrant

00:43:31.100 --> 00:43:34.120
commercial practice.

00:43:34.120 --> 00:43:35.600
Once Fujisawa puts knife

00:43:35.600 --> 00:43:39.280
to block he must assess the
block's grain at every juncture.

00:43:39.280 --> 00:43:42.260
Unlike the composition
of steel for instance,

00:43:42.260 --> 00:43:46.970
internally the wood possesses
a unique pattern of growth

00:43:46.970 --> 00:43:50.640
and fibers can deviate from
the straight growth creating an

00:43:50.640 --> 00:43:55.110
internal composition
of a mix of grains.

00:43:55.110 --> 00:43:56.690
Fujisawa sees his challenge

00:43:56.690 --> 00:43:59.590
in the individual
nature of block poses.

00:43:59.590 --> 00:44:01.790
He characterizes
it as a face-off

00:44:01.790 --> 00:44:04.340
between nature and human skill.

00:44:04.340 --> 00:44:06.920
Carving into the grain of course
can be damaging to the wood

00:44:06.920 --> 00:44:08.790
and works against
the cut of the knife.

00:44:08.790 --> 00:44:12.770
Carving with the grain the
knife moves along in parallel.

00:44:12.770 --> 00:44:15.290
So, Fujisawa feels his
way across the block

00:44:15.290 --> 00:44:16.800
as he wields his knife,

00:44:16.800 --> 00:44:20.290
anticipating these internal
traffic jams in the wood.

00:44:20.290 --> 00:44:24.480
One true test of the overall
quality of woodblock print lies

00:44:24.480 --> 00:44:28.270
in these inked-out lines, the
[inaudible], the curved lines.

00:44:28.270 --> 00:44:31.980
And if any of you have had
the experience of going

00:44:31.980 --> 00:44:36.190
through an ukiyo-e exhibition
around Japan I've observed

00:44:36.190 --> 00:44:40.140
that viewers this is one of
the areas where they sigh

00:44:40.140 --> 00:44:44.410
and they pause over this moment
of these beautiful curved lines.

00:44:44.410 --> 00:44:46.740
Although computer
technology can now aid

00:44:46.740 --> 00:44:50.530
in carving these lines Fujisawa
hazards it's not the same

00:44:50.530 --> 00:44:52.520
movement as the human hand.

00:44:52.520 --> 00:44:55.770
Therein lies his
conceptualization of kokoro,

00:44:55.770 --> 00:44:59.530
this mindfulness, as
it ties to his craft.

00:44:59.530 --> 00:45:02.700
Lest his arguments sound
dubious he proceeds,

00:45:02.700 --> 00:45:06.440
when he carves a masterwork he
may be transported into the mind

00:45:06.440 --> 00:45:09.590
of an artist and effectively
be able to read them.

00:45:09.590 --> 00:45:13.020
The physical process also
yielding a spiritual connection

00:45:13.020 --> 00:45:17.170
if you will that a
computer cannot facilitate.

00:45:17.170 --> 00:45:21.110
In contrast, when he observes
computer-generated print designs

00:45:21.110 --> 00:45:24.510
he believes their feeling,
their [inaudible] isn't good.

00:45:24.510 --> 00:45:26.400
Even if an artist
approaches a project

00:45:26.400 --> 00:45:29.770
with certain intent the
mediating computer disables

00:45:29.770 --> 00:45:32.290
dimensions of the human idea.

00:45:32.290 --> 00:45:35.040
He believes there's an
infinitely more variation

00:45:35.040 --> 00:45:38.890
and nuance to the types of
lines humans can create.

00:45:38.890 --> 00:45:43.200
A computer-generated image of a
chrysanthemum for instance maybe

00:45:43.200 --> 00:45:46.250
so finely executed
that it is impossible

00:45:46.250 --> 00:45:48.190
for a human hand to carve.

00:45:48.190 --> 00:45:52.320
But if the human hand depicts
these lines it will only draw

00:45:52.320 --> 00:45:55.590
what can physically
it can manage,

00:45:55.590 --> 00:45:59.030
thereby vesting the
rendering of the blossom

00:45:59.030 --> 00:46:00.770
with a subjective expression.

00:46:00.770 --> 00:46:03.790
And I think this is where
that's when people are sighing

00:46:03.790 --> 00:46:06.040
at these curved lines, you
know there's that transfer,

00:46:06.040 --> 00:46:09.040
that feeling of something
ineluctably human

00:46:09.040 --> 00:46:12.690
if you will about
that execution.

00:46:12.690 --> 00:46:15.850
And in a case where the artist
fails to be as successful

00:46:15.850 --> 00:46:20.100
in depicting lines the carver
can go in and improve the work.

00:46:20.100 --> 00:46:22.780
Or simply put, there's something
accessible and authentic

00:46:22.780 --> 00:46:24.530
about an image whose composition

00:46:24.530 --> 00:46:29.110
and production we can
finesse ourselves.

00:46:29.110 --> 00:46:31.360
I'd like to come full circle

00:46:31.360 --> 00:46:36.450
to consider Sato Keizo's
selection of a view of Naruto.

00:46:36.450 --> 00:46:41.240
Like many ukiyo-e landscapes
it's a pleasing image in itself.

00:46:41.240 --> 00:46:43.180
The landscape also appeals

00:46:43.180 --> 00:46:46.660
because like larger-than-life
Mount Fuji it maintains

00:46:46.660 --> 00:46:48.510
contemporary significance.

00:46:48.510 --> 00:46:52.290
Hiroshige's scenic portrayal
of the tidal whirlpools

00:46:52.290 --> 00:46:55.650
in the Naruto Strait can still
be witnessed today in a channel

00:46:55.650 --> 00:47:00.170
between Naruto in
Tokushima and Awaji Island.

00:47:00.170 --> 00:47:03.490
Art historically the print's
content also offers its own

00:47:03.490 --> 00:47:06.170
narrative, it's believed
to be one

00:47:06.170 --> 00:47:09.370
of the three tryptics Hiroshige
created in his last year

00:47:09.370 --> 00:47:13.440
of life observing the theme
sun, moon and flowers,

00:47:13.440 --> 00:47:17.530
the whirlpool rapids whimsically
depicting the flower theme.

00:47:17.530 --> 00:47:20.140
There is in short, much
to be made of it revered

00:47:20.140 --> 00:47:22.700
as a pretty picture
and a visual work

00:47:22.700 --> 00:47:26.100
that these days we can consume
for free in any proximity

00:47:26.100 --> 00:47:30.840
of a screen or a museum
shot or for real here.

00:47:30.840 --> 00:47:35.100
So, the crux of the question
remains, does the making matter

00:47:35.100 --> 00:47:38.140
as long as we enjoy
the visual image?

00:47:38.140 --> 00:47:41.470
Japanese woodblock printing is
often discounted among Japan's

00:47:41.470 --> 00:47:44.540
rich tradition of
arts and crafts,

00:47:44.540 --> 00:47:46.610
devoid of any explicit use value

00:47:46.610 --> 00:47:50.350
like a ceramic tea bowl
or a bamboo basket.

00:47:50.350 --> 00:47:53.270
Historically viewed as a
reproductive technology rather

00:47:53.270 --> 00:47:56.420
than a refined craft its
artisans also haven't always

00:47:56.420 --> 00:47:59.710
made the annals of
traditional Japanese arts.

00:47:59.710 --> 00:48:03.330
But ukiyo-e comes to us
today both as historic prints

00:48:03.330 --> 00:48:06.490
and refined artworks because
of the vast compendium

00:48:06.490 --> 00:48:09.320
of hand techniques and the
[inaudible] materials it

00:48:09.320 --> 00:48:12.770
integrates in order to
create a single sheet.

00:48:12.770 --> 00:48:14.260
Through the artisans

00:48:14.260 --> 00:48:16.980
who preserve it today
ukiyo-e are documents

00:48:16.980 --> 00:48:20.260
of living culture beyond
their visual value,

00:48:20.260 --> 00:48:22.980
that such a universally
appealing image is still

00:48:22.980 --> 00:48:26.830
generated primarily of organic
materials almost exclusively

00:48:26.830 --> 00:48:31.360
with human hands and by a
community of local individuals

00:48:31.360 --> 00:48:35.030
who know one another, are
values of making and of living

00:48:35.030 --> 00:48:37.270
and working that
offer new relevance

00:48:37.270 --> 00:48:39.560
in the virtual worlds of today.

